##I am a private hospital nurses, although not "national team" , but I went to Wuhan, to help treat patients

Micro Signal Xinminzhoukan

Function description, depth and angle —— this is what we can do.

Some people say that medical workers like us are volunteers, not "national team" . But we don't care about that. My colleague here, a doctor who used to run his own clinic and came to support him, said, "since I'm here, I don't care if I live or die. " I didn't think about what he said, i just want to be able to do my job and help the patient. Well, I guess that helps.

DICTATION: Li Ruirui

Arrangement: Wang Yu

On February 19, the high-speed train from Nanjing South Railway Station, my wish is finally coming true: This train will take me to Wuhan! In the car I just sent a message to tell my family about it, they were very worried: "How can you go to Wuhan at this time? ! " I replied: "I want to help treat the sick! "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Li Ruirui is at his post in Wuhan

In fact, just before the Spring Festival outbreak, I would like to go to Wuhan to help. I am a nurse, but in the private hospital work, through the unit arrangement to support Wuhan the opportunity is quite small. I thought about going to Wuhan First, but I couldn't get a ticket for that period of time, so I volunteered online.

In the online volunteer organization, young friends collect information from various channels such as Weibo and Wechat to seek help. For example, in places such as Wuhan, there are patients who have difficulty in getting medical treatment, and there are elderly people and children who have no one to take care of them. After contacting the parties concerned to verify, then help them contact the hospital, the government, the media and so on, try to help them solve the problem. Often in order to implement the help program, contact the various units, I also have to work until two or three in the morning or even to work all night.

But I still want to go to Wuhan, because I am a nurse after all, hope to be able to contribute my professional skills to the first line. I saw on the news that there was a serious shortage of medical personnel there, and I thought I could go and help. As for the risk of infection, I really didn't think much of that. Maybe because I am a strong man, want to do things must find a way to do it.

Finally, I read in a group that the Wuchang District Council had commissioned a health management company to recruit qualified medical staff to support local hospitals in the fight against new pneumonia. I signed up right away, and then I got in, and I was so happy.

We are supporting Wuhan No. 7 Hospital, a designated local hospital for fever patients. One of the wards has been taken over by our team of medical volunteers from all over the country. We have a team of more than a dozen people, and I am the same as the private hospital staff, there are their own clinics of doctors. I didn't know any of them before, but as soon as I got to the hospital, I went to work and became colleagues.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Li Ruirui and colleagues at Wuhan No. 7 Hospital

Our Ward has admitted patients with mild fever, of whom new coronary pneumonia has been confirmed. What I do is a lot of trivialities, such as dispensing medicine, dispensing medicine, distributing rice, sterilizing the ward, taking the patients'temperature, blood pressure, blood sugar, blood oxygen, drawing their blood, taking throat swabs, and then trying to answer the patients'questions, give them what they want. For example, a patient might say, "I want to have a nucleic acid test. Can you apply for me? " Someone might ask, "nurse, why didn't I get the results of my last test? " Someone might ask for another mask. On some days, several patients were not used to the food arranged by the hospital and wanted to eat instant noodles. I went to the back office and told them I got instant noodles. Some of the patients wanted steamed bread for breakfast, so I went to try to solve it.

Everything was easy, but we usually had only one doctor and one nurse per shift, and I had thirty patients to deal with at the same time, as long as the patients took turns calling me, plus I had my own tasks to complete, eight, nine hours, barely a break. Only every time a patient was given a meal, and they all ate it together, I might have ten minutes of complete rest.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Li Ruirui (right) with colleagues

I knew I had to wear full protective gear in my hospital room in Wuhan, and I knew it would be uncomfortable, but I didn't think about it; I hadn't worn it in my previous nursing post. I think all the difficulties will be defeated by me, but the reality is much more difficult than I thought.

In the suit will soon be full of sweat, and then evaporation dry, and then sweat, dry, eight or nine hours, the whole body from time to time to soak in sweat. When I got back from work, the first thing I did was finish a bottle of mineral water in one Gulp, and then I rushed into the shower to take a shower. I felt really dirty and smelly, shower Gel, shampoo and conditioner should be used at least three times before you feel comfortable.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Li rui-rui in everyday life

Wearing a mask and goggles for a long time, after taking off, my face was like a claw scratched, everywhere is indentation. I am usually a pretty love of people, now every time after work do not dare to look at their own face in the mirror. Not only does it look scary, but the pressure hurts like hell. Indentation only rely on their own kneading a bit before bed to apply mask to ease. It's been more than 10 days here, and we're running out of face masks that the nurses brought with us. The woman who lives next door came to me and asked me to borrow some toothpaste and put it on her face to see if it would help with the pain.

When I worked at my own hospital, I was reluctant to take the night shift; but here, the night shift was mandatory. The "big night shift" started at 12 PM and ended at 8 am the next day, but by 5 am I had to take blood and throat swabs from patients who needed to be tested, often taking samples, and by Dawn.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the night shift, Li Ruirui takes a nap when he has a little time off

I couldn't eat or drink during the whole time I was in my hazmat suit, and the first few days I got to work I was so hungry at mealtime that I got used to it. In fact, it's not just that I can't eat or drink at work. To avoid going to the bathroom during that time, I stop eating five hours before my shift starts, sometimes just once a day.

In fact, no matter how difficult it is, I am willing to come, no one asked me, called me. And I'm really happy that I'm doing this. I think other volunteers are really hard work, such as the volunteer driver who drives us to and from work. Sometimes it's almost one o'clock in the morning when I get off work, and he still waits for me to take me to my apartment.

The other day, when I was disinfecting the ward, a patient said to me, "Rui Rui, you are so diligent. " I said, "I want you to get out of the hospital early. " These two days, people will also be discharged, see them smiling to say goodbye to me, it was the happiest time of my life when I felt like I could work 24 hours a day and it was worth it.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Li Ruirui cheers for the patient
